prompt:
My JavaScript page is becoming really slow after repeatedly adding and clearing elements, like there's a memory leak. Here is a simplified version of what I'm doing:

```javascript
function renderItems(items) {
    const container = document.getElementById('container');
    for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
        const el = document.createElement('div');
        el.textContent = items[i].name;
        el.addEventListener('click', () => alert(items[i].name));
        container.appendChild(el);
    }
}

function clearItems() {
    document.getElementById('container').innerHTML = '';
}
```

After many render/clear cycles the browser tab eventually becomes unresponsive. What's the cause and how do I fix it?

ground_truth:
```javascript
function renderItems(items) {
    const container = document.getElementById('container');
    const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();
    for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
        const el = document.createElement('div');
        el.textContent = items[i].name;
        const name = items[i].name; // capture per iteration
        el.addEventListener('click', () => alert(name));
        fragment.appendChild(el);
    }
    container.appendChild(fragment);
}

function clearItems() {
    const container = document.getElementById('container');
    while (container.firstChild) {
        container.removeChild(container.firstChild);
    }
}
```

Setting `innerHTML = ''` detaches DOM nodes but listeners and closures referencing them remain in memory until garbage-collected. Using a `DocumentFragment` batches DOM reflows, capturing `name` per iteration avoids closure pitfalls, and the `while` loop via `removeChild` ensures proper detachment so listeners can be released.

